# Roadmap ④ — SQL State Store + real Alertmanager, live E2E (2026-07-17)

Stack (all local docker, $0, torn down after):
  postgres:16-alpine        :15432  (db platform_state)
  prom/alertmanager:v0.28.1 :19093  (webhook receiver → host :18079, group_wait 2s)
  onprem_webhook_api        :18079 / :18080 (TWO replicas, same
                            PLATFORM_STATE_DSN=postgresql://…/platform_state)

Code: src/agents/ai/state_store.py (opt-in seam; DSN unset = JSONL unchanged),
wired into onprem_approvals + onprem_incidents. Offline tests via sqlite3.

## 1. Real Alertmanager delivery (not a hand-crafted payload)
  POST alert to Alertmanager /api/v2/alerts (KubePodCrashLooping, critical,
  service=payments-api) → 200
  → Alertmanager grouped and delivered its native webhook payload to
    /webhook/alertmanager on replica-1
  → 4-step pipeline → P2 APPROVE → parked APR-47069492 **in PostgreSQL**:
    platform_state row 1: APPROVAL APR-47069492 (status pending)

## 2. Cross-replica shared state (the reason the store exists)
  replica-2 (:18080, separate process) GET /pending → 1 [APR-47069492]
  POST /approve/APR-47069492 **on replica-2**
    → approved, executed [ONPREM-CreateChangeRequest], INC-FA6F7B43
  replica-1 (:18079) immediately: /pending → 0, /incidents → [INC-FA6F7B43]
  (JSONL could never do this across nodes — this unlocks replicas>1 for the
   Helm chart once the DSN is set.)

## 3. Durability across full process restart
  killed BOTH replicas → started fresh process → /incidents → [INC-FA6F7B43]

## 4. Ground truth in PostgreSQL (psql)
  id | kind     | key
   1 | APPROVAL | APR-47069492   (pending)
   2 | APPROVAL | APR-47069492   (approved — append-only, latest wins)
   3 | INCIDENT | INC-FA6F7B43
  Same append-only lifecycle as the JSONL files, now replica-shareable.

Verdict: real Alertmanager → webhook → approval gate → execute → incident,
with every state transition living in PostgreSQL and shared live between two
replicas. Default posture unchanged (no DSN = JSONL, gate suite proves
non-contamination both ways).
